<author><name><![CDATA[blargg]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-05-30T06:38:46-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-05-30T06:38:46-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6426&amp;p=62102#p62102</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6426&amp;p=62102#p62102"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[What should write-only registers return when read? ($200x)]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6426&amp;p=62102#p62102"><![CDATA[
I just had some code write $FF to $2002, then read back $2001 at 10 msec invervals:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">msec 0  ... 260 270 ... 340 350 360 370 ... 440 450 460 470 480 490 500 510 520 <br />read FF ... FF  EF  ... EF  CD  CD  C9  ... C9  C1  81  81  81  81  81  81  00</div><br />So the last value written (and probably read) gets held for a while, but slowly decays to zero by around 520 msec (half a second), but at different rates for each bit. I imagine the decay rates vary slightly for each NES unit.<br /><br /><strong>EDIT:</strong> Haha, as expected, the decay rate is affected significantly by the PPU temperature. I wrote a second test that accurately times how long it takes for each bit to decay. You could use this in a game to tell whether the NES had been on for a long time, perhaps in a scene like in Metal Gear Solid  for PSX where it examines your memory card and says things based on what other games you've played.<br /><br />Just powered on, taking measurement every 10 seconds or so (114 clocks per unit):<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent"> 7    6    5    4    3    2    1    0<br />253F 2085 1D30 15DB 27D1 1EB0 214C 2A95 <br />237E 1E9F 1B80 14B7 25DE 1D5D 1F96 283A <br />2293 1DE3 1B13 146D 2515 1CE1 1F55 278D <br />222E 1DAA 1A85 143A 2470 1CA3 1EF4 26ED <br />2180 1D28 1A2D 13D9 2432 1C4E 1E73 25EB <br />2093 1CAA 19D0 13AA 2391 1BF0 1DEA 25E7 <br />207E 1C51 1980 1376 2343 1B9C 1D8B 255B <br />202A 1C11 192B 1331 22CD 1B39 1D62 24EE <br />1F5A 1B6F 188F 12B2 220A 1AE6 1CE3 23E3 <br />... after several minutes ...<br />16B5 13E6 11A9 0E01 1946 149A 15F5 1A4D <br />16A2 13E0 1184 0DE3 1914 14AC 15C5 1A32</div><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Sun May 30, 2010 6:38 am</p><hr />
